<p>St Petersburg residents benefit from substantial solar incentives that make renewable energy installations highly attractive. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit on the total cost of solar panel systems through 2032, reducing to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to all components including panels, inverters, installation, and permitting costs.</p>

<p>Florida offers additional advantages through its solar-friendly policies, including no state income tax on solar investments and property tax exemptions for solar installations. Duke Energy participates in net metering programs, allowing St Petersburg solar customers to sell excess electricity back to the grid at retail rates. While Duke Energy doesn't currently offer direct solar rebates, they provide energy efficiency rebates for qualifying HVAC systems, including up to \$1,500 for high-efficiency heat pumps and additional rebates for smart thermostats and duct sealing services.</p>

